      <children>
            <TextArea editable="false" layoutX="22.0" layoutY="16.0" prefHeight="367.0" prefWidth="596.0" text="Marble Lab allows the user to manipulate marble-like particles on screen for the purpose of observing forces, &#10;momentum, and acceleration in action. &#10;&#10;Settings:&#10;-Show ids: Displays the id of every particle &#10;-Disable Boundaries: Particles can go off screen&#10;-Paused: Pauses the simulation&#10;-Friction: Particles slow down based on coefficient&#10;&#10;Tools:&#10;-Edit Particle: Edit the properties of a particle. After selecting a particle, it can be edited ont he right-hand dashboard.&#10;-Move Particle: Drag a particle (removes velocity from particle)&#10;-Add Particle: Add a new particle&#10;-Delete Particle: Delete an existing particle&#10;-Add Force: Adds force for a given duration to a particle&#10;-Track Particle: Adds particle information to the chart at the bottom of the screen.&#10;&#10;Tool Settings:&#10;-Particle Settings: Customize the properties of new particles to add.&#10;-Force Settings: Change both force and duration for adding forces.&#10;-Gravitation Settings: Change the multiplier for gravity.&#10;&#10;Sources:&#10;http://youtube.com/watch?v=LPzyNOHY3A4 - Collision algorithm &#10;https://gamedevelopment.tutsplus.com/tutorials/introduction-to-javafx-for-game-development--cms-23835 - JavaFX gameloop&#10;https://stackoverflow.com/questions/52653836/maven-shade-javafx-runtime-components-are-missing - Running JavaFX&#10;https://fxdocs.github.io/docs/html5/ - JavaFX documentation.&#10;https://www.tutorialspoint.com/javafx/javafx_event_handling.htm - events&#10;https://www.genuinecoder.com/javafx-get-screen-size-of-all-connected-monitors/ - screen size&#10;https://docs.oracle.com/javafx/2/ui_controls/table-view.htm - tableview&#10;https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Z1W4E2d4Yxo - Getting started with scenebuilder&#10;https://docs.oracle.com/javafx/2/get_started/fxml_tutorial.htm - Using FXML" />
